<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The yellow wing colouration is much more extensive on the female than on the male. Similar sexual dimorphism in wing colouration also occurs in other 
<taxonomicName authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, e.g., 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. chrysopygus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="chrysopygus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. chrysopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. flavofascium" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="flavofascium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. flavofascium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The male from the Brazilian state Amazonas was collected in humid forest along a small stream (
<normalizedToken originalValue="“igarapé”">&quot;igarape&quot;</normalizedToken>
). The female from Amazonas was collected in a 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“campinarana”">&quot;campinarana&quot;</normalizedToken>
: a type of vegetation occurring in flat, sandy soils prone to waterlogging, usually dominated by thin trees (pers. comm. G.F.G. Miranda).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
